@page "/tenants/solo"
@inject ITenantProvider Tenant

<h1>Solo vs multi-site</h1>

<p>
    <code>TenantMiddleware</code> auto-detects single-site hosts. There are two cases that
    end up in the same place:
</p>

<ol>
    <li>The host did <strong>not</strong> register an <code>ITenantSource</code> at all.</li>
    <li>The registered manager returned <code>null</code> for the current host name.</li>
</ol>

<p>
    Either way, the middleware seeds <code>ITenantRepository</code> with
    <code>Tenant.Solo</code> — a sentinel with <code>Id == Guid.Empty</code> and
    <code>Domain == "*"</code>. The result: <code>ITenantProvider.Current</code> is never
    <code>null</code>, settings always surface either persisted overrides or the
    compile-time defaults, and pages don't need null-checks.
</p>

<section class="card">
    <h2>Right now</h2>
    <dl>
        <dt>Id</dt>      <dd><code>@Tenant.Current?.Id</code></dd>
        <dt>Domain</dt>  <dd>@Tenant.Current?.Domain</dd>
        <dt>IsSolo</dt>  <dd>@Tenant.Current?.IsSolo</dd>
        <dt>Vars</dt>    <dd>@(Tenant.Current?.Variables.Count ?? 0)</dd>
    </dl>
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>How to flip the demo</h2>
    <pre>// Program.cs
// Comment this out to force solo-mode globally:
// builder.Services.AddScoped&lt;ITenantSource, InMemoryTenantManager&gt;();</pre>
</section>
